----
== YS Addresses YAML's Major Real World Limitations

* Composability - Include data from external sources
  * Files, URLS, Shell commands, Env vars, Databases, etc

* Transformations - 100s of standard functions to apply
  * Merge, Filter, Map, Reduce, Sort, etc

* Conditionals
  * Craft data based on runtime conditions

* Interpolation
  * Expand variables and expressions in strings

* Variables
  * Store values for reuse


----
== Composing YAML files

$ vim -O composed1.yaml vars1.yaml
$ ys -Y composed1.yaml

$ vim composed2.yaml
$ ys -Y composed2.yaml

$ vim composed3.yaml
$ ys -Y composed3.yaml


----
== Conditional YAML

$ vim conditional.yaml

$ ys -Y conditional.yaml

$ CAT=1 ys -Y conditional.yaml

$ DOG=1 ys -Y conditional.yaml

$ CAT=1 DOG=1 ys -Y conditional.yaml

$ DEBUG=1 ys -Y conditional.yaml


----
== How a YAML Loader Works

* A YAML Loader is a Stack of Transformations
  * Text File -> Native Data Structure

* Text File          -> (READ)      -> Code Points
* Code Points        -> (SCAN)      -> Tokens
* Tokens             -> (PARSE)     -> Parse Events
  * https://play.yaml.io/main/parser?input=LSBbYWJjXTogMTIzCg==

* Parse Events       -> (COMPOSE)   -> Node Tree

* Node Tree          -> (RESOLVE)   -> Resolved Node Tree
  * All nodes have tags - explicit or implicit

* Resolved Node Tree -> (CONSTRUCT) -> Native Data Structure
  * Tags are mapped to functions (not types)


----
== How YS Works

* YS compiles YAMLScript to Clojure
  * Then evaluates the Clojure with its runtime

* The YS compiler is implemented as a YAML Loader
  * Loads to an AST rather than a data structure

$ ys -ce  'say: "Hello, $(ENV.USER)"'
$ ys -cde 'say: "Hello, $(ENV.USER)"'

* YAML's unique features make YS possible
  * Plain Scalars (unquoted strings)
  * Implicit tag resolution (taken to the extreme)

* YS supports tags for function calls, BTW
  $ vim tag-calls.yaml
  $ ys -Y tag-calls.yaml


----
== YS for DevOps

* YS wants to be adopted by all DevOps tools that use YAML
  * Configurable drop-in YAML loader for:
    * Kubernetes
    * Helm
    * GitHub Actions
    * Ansible
    * AWS CDK
    * Docker Compose
    * CircleCI

* Not there yet

* But users can use YS today in their DevOps configs


----
== HelmYS

* HelmYS is a YS-based Helm Post-Renderer
  * Use YS in your Helm charts today!
  * Relpace or combine with Go template syntax

* https://yamlscript.org/helmys/


